</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E35B9301FFD5AC77F1632601FE58FCC7" blockId="6.[361,476,830,852]" box="[361,476,830,852]" pageId="6">: unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E35B9301FFD5AC77F15E265AFDC9FC04" blockId="6.[340,1248,868,919]" pageId="6">
E t y m o l o g y: This remarkable species is dedicated to Sinan Anlaú, 
<collectingRegion id="21205DE3FFD5AC77F460265AFB27FCE9" box="[1130,1187,868,890]" country="Turkey" name="Izmir" pageId="6">Izmir</collectingRegion>
, who discovered the 
<typeStatus id="3C5F2DA3FFD5AC77F1E726BFFDCDFC04" box="[493,585,897,919]" pageId="6">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E35B9301FFD5AC77F15E2698FD37FC64" blockId="6.[340,1248,934,1015]" pageId="6">C o m m e n t: The question whether the conspicuously long abdominal segment III is a character shared by both sexes or confined to males can be clarified only when females become available for examination.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E35B9301FFD5AC77F15E2138FB0EFB02" blockId="6.[340,1248,1030,1169]" pageId="6">
C o m p a r a t i v e n o t e s: This highly distinctive species is easily identified among its congeners by several unique characters: the morphology of the male elytra (pronounced lateral folds, absence of pronounced sutural carinae), the elongated abdominal segment III, the absence of a process on the male tergite 
<collectionCode id="85F50BC4FFD5AC77F4092161FBACFBE7" box="[1027,1064,1119,1140]" pageId="6">VII</collectionCode>
, and the shape of the male tergite VIII with a pair of pronounced processes at the posterior margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E35B9301FFD5AC77F15E219FFB42FAF4" blockId="6.[340,1248,1184,1580]" pageId="6">
In order to account for this species, the key in 
<bibRefCitation id="8775EEF0FFD5AC77F320219FFC4FFB25" author="ASSING V" box="[810,971,1184,1207]" pageId="6" pagination="903 - 1006" refId="ref20419" refString="ASSING V. (2005 a): A revision of the species of Geostiba THOMSON and Tropimenelytron PACE of the Eastern Mediterranean, the Caucasus, and adjacent regions (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae, Aleocharinae). - Linzer biol. Beitr. 37 (2): 903 - 1006." type="journal article" year="2005">ASSING (2005a)</bibRefCitation>
is modified as follows: 107 Abdominal segment III conspicuously elongated, ratio of width (across posterior margin) and length (from anterior margin of paratergite to posterior margin of tergite): &lt;1.3 (
<figureCitation id="7BDF8F84FFD5AC77F23C21D1FD06FA97" box="[566,642,1263,1284]" captionStart="Figs 13-19" captionStartId="5.[340,380,1630,1650]" captionTargetBox="[341,1203,755,1595]" captionTargetId="figure-125@5.[340,1211,1152,1605]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs 13-19: Geostiba anlasi sp.n. (holotype): (13) habitus; (14) forebody; (15) anterior part of" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5434900" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5434900/files/figure.png" pageId="6">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
).: elytra with pronounced lateral folds (
<figureCitation id="7BDF8F84FFD5AC77F43421D1FB3DFA97" box="[1086,1209,1263,1284]" captionStart="Figs 13-19" captionStartId="5.[340,380,1630,1650]" captionTargetBox="[341,1203,755,1595]" captionTargetId="figure-125@5.[340,1211,1152,1605]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs 13-19: Geostiba anlasi sp.n. (holotype): (13) habitus; (14) forebody; (15) anterior part of" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5434900" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5434900/files/figure.png" pageId="6">Figs 14, 16</figureCitation>
); posterior margin of tergite VIII with pair of pronounced processes (
<figureCitation id="7BDF8F84FFD5AC77F461203BFB3CFA89" box="[1131,1208,1285,1306]" captionStart="Figs 13-19" captionStartId="5.[340,380,1630,1650]" captionTargetBox="[341,1203,755,1595]" captionTargetId="figure-125@5.[340,1211,1152,1605]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs 13-19: Geostiba anlasi sp.n. (holotype): (13) habitus; (14) forebody; (15) anterior part of" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5434900" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5434900/files/figure.png" pageId="6">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
); median lobe of aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation id="7BDF8F84FFD5AC77F2C22022FC8BFAA2" box="[712,783,1308,1329]" captionStart="Figs 13-19" captionStartId="5.[340,380,1630,1650]" captionTargetBox="[341,1203,755,1595]" captionTargetId="figure-125@5.[340,1211,1152,1605]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs 13-19: Geostiba anlasi sp.n. (holotype): (13) habitus; (14) forebody; (15) anterior part of" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5434900" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5434900/files/figure.png" pageId="6">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
. Western 
<collectingCountry id="9BF3D391FFD5AC77F3642022FC41FAA2" box="[878,965,1308,1329]" name="Turkey" pageId="6">Anatolia</collectingCountry>
: 
<collectingRegion id="21205DE3FFD5AC77F3C42022FBD8FAA2" box="[974,1116,1308,1329]" country="Turkey" name="Izmir" pageId="6">Izmir province</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation id="7BDF8F84FFD5AC77F4632022FB2DFAA2" box="[1129,1193,1308,1329]" captionStart="Map 3" captionStartId="10.[340,385,1651,1671]" captionTargetBox="[340,1254,1088,1640]" captionTargetId="figure-22@10.[340,1254,1088,1640]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Map 3: Distributions of Geostiba nifica (black circles), G. atromontis (white circles), G. aydinica (grey circles), G. anlasi (large black square), G. biformis (small black squares), and G. renneri (white square) in western and southwestern Anatolia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5434908" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5434908/files/figure.png" pageId="6">Map 3</figureCitation>
) ....... ................................................................................................................. 
<taxonomicName id="24E4E882FFD5AC77F45E200DFB28FADB" authority="Homson, 1974" authorityName="Homson" authorityYear="1974" box="[1108,1196,1331,1352]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geostiba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anlasi" status="sp.n.">
<emphasis id="D1904F13FFD5AC77F45E200DFB28FADB" box="[1108,1196,1331,1352]" italics="true" pageId="6">G. anlasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="CAA3F268FFD5AC77F4B8200DFB64FADB" box="[1202,1248,1331,1352]" pageId="6" rank="species">sp.n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
- Abdominal segment III strongly transverse, at least 1.5-1.6 times as wide as long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E35B9301FFD5AC77F1BE2056FB5BF9BF" blockId="6.[340,1248,1184,1580]" pageId="6">
: elytra without pronounced lateral folds; tergite VIII without pair of pronounced processes; aedeagus of different morphology, without cristal process....................107a 107a: tergite 
<collectionCode id="85F50BC4FFD5AC77F20620A0FDA9FA20" box="[524,557,1438,1459]" pageId="6">VII</collectionCode>
near posterior margin with – often weakly defined – subcircular median tubercle (Fig. 
<quantity id="241C3EE4FFD5AC77F28B208BFD47FA59" box="[641,707,1461,1482]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.1148" pageId="6" unit="in" value="162.0">162 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation id="8775EEF0FFD5AC77F2C7208BFCD1FA59" author="ASSING V" box="[717,853,1461,1482]" pageId="6" pagination="903 - 1006" refId="ref20419" refString="ASSING V. (2005 a): A revision of the species of Geostiba THOMSON and Tropimenelytron PACE of the Eastern Mediterranean, the Caucasus, and adjacent regions (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae, Aleocharinae). - Linzer biol. Beitr. 37 (2): 903 - 1006." type="journal article" year="2005">Assing 2005a</bibRefCitation>
and 
<figureCitation id="7BDF8F84FFD5AC77F387208BFC6FFA59" box="[909,1003,1461,1482]" captionStart="Figs 98-107" captionStartId="32.[340,380,1270,1290]" captionTargetBox="[340,1238,425,1235]" captionTargetId="figure-4@32.[340,1253,768,1245]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="Figs 98-107: Geostiba orduica sp.n.: (98) habitus; (99) forebody; (100) head in lateral view; (101)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5434942" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5434942/files/figure.png" pageId="6">Fig. A99</figureCitation>
: 200), which may be reduced to various degrees; elytra with distinct microsculpture and almost or completely matt. Species confined to the Taygetos range (
<collectingCountry id="9BF3D391FFD5AC77F3DA20DCFB9DFA64" box="[976,1049,1506,1527]" name="Greece" pageId="6">Greece</collectingCountry>
: 
<collectingRegion id="21205DE3FFD5AC77F42820DCFB20FA64" box="[1058,1188,1506,1527]" country="Greece" name="Peloponnisos" pageId="6">Pelopónnisos</collectingRegion>
) or the Caucasus region..................................................................................................108 - tergite 
<collectionCode id="85F50BC4FFD5AC77F1F72329FD9AF9BF" box="[509,542,1559,1580]" pageId="6">VII</collectionCode>
unmodified..........................................................................................109
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E35B9301FFD5AC77F15E2305FCBEF970" blockId="6.[340,1248,1595,1763]" pageId="6">
D i s t r i b u t i o n a n d b i o n o m i c s: 
<taxonomicName id="24E4E882FFD5AC77F35A2305FC75F9C2" authorityName="Homson" authorityYear="1974" box="[848,1009,1595,1617]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geostiba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anlasi">
<emphasis id="D1904F13FFD5AC77F35A2305FC75F9C2" box="[848,1009,1595,1617]" italics="true" pageId="6">Geostiba anlasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be endemic to the Ak Da÷ and adjacent mountains on the peninsula approximately 
<quantity id="241C3EE4FFD5AC77F4062366FBD4F9FD" box="[1036,1104,1624,1646]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="6" unit="km" value="60.0">60 km</quantity>
WNW 
<collectingRegion id="21205DE3FFD5AC77F4A32366FB5BF9FD" box="[1193,1247,1624,1646]" country="Turkey" name="Izmir" pageId="6">Izmir</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation id="7BDF8F84FFD5AC77F151234BFE24F918" box="[347,416,1653,1675]" captionStart="Map 3" captionStartId="10.[340,385,1651,1671]" captionTargetBox="[340,1254,1088,1640]" captionTargetId="figure-22@10.[340,1254,1088,1640]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Map 3: Distributions of Geostiba nifica (black circles), G. atromontis (white circles), G. aydinica (grey circles), G. anlasi (large black square), G. biformis (small black squares), and G. renneri (white square) in western and southwestern Anatolia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5434908" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5434908/files/figure.png" pageId="6">Map 3</figureCitation>
), a conclusion mainly based on the restricted distributions of its Turkish consubgeners. The 
<typeStatus id="3C5F2DA3FFD5AC77F1DE23ACFDA9F93B" box="[468,557,1682,1704]" pageId="6">holotype</typeStatus>
was found under a stone on a grassy slope at an elevation of only 
<specimenCount id="F5E25888FFD5AC77F15E238EFE26F956" box="[340,418,1712,1734]" pageId="6" type="generic">
<quantity id="241C3EE4FFD5AC77F15E238EFE1AF956" box="[340,414,1712,1734]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.2" pageId="6" unit="m" value="420.0">420 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
Subsequent sifting of the surrounding area yielded some specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="24E4E882FFD5AC77F4CD238EFE20F970" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geostiba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="euboica">
<emphasis id="D1904F13FFD5AC77F4CD238EFE20F970" italics="true" pageId="6">G. euboica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but no additional material of 
<taxonomicName id="24E4E882FFD5AC77F2DD23F0FCB0F970" authorityName="Homson" authorityYear="1974" box="[727,820,1741,1763]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geostiba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anlasi">
<emphasis id="D1904F13FFD5AC77F2DD23F0FCB0F970" box="[727,820,1741,1763]" italics="true" pageId="6">G. anlasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
